\f0\fs26 \cf0 # Week 10 Appendix: Law as Instrument of Rule\
\
This week is a concentrated demonstration of authoritarian consolidation through executive fiat, legal intimidation, and weaponized bureaucracy. The White House escalated its campaign against the legal system\'97issuing and bargaining away punitive orders against major law firms, directing the attorney general to investigate opposing lawyers, and backing impeachment threats and structural attacks on federal courts. Simultaneously, Trump signed sweeping election orders imposing documentary proof-of-citizenship, empowering federal agencies and DOGE to police voter rolls, and framing mass disenfranchisement as \'93integrity.\'94 Immigration and protest are fused into a security paradigm: the Alien Enemies Act deportations, defiance of court orders, social-media vetting of students, and high-profile detentions of pro\uc0\u8209 Palestinian academics show citizenship stratified by ideology and origin. Inside the state, mass civil-service and union-busting orders, DOGE penetration of Social Security, and deep cuts to HHS, public health, and labor oversight hollow out neutral administration and social protection. Overlaying all of this is a chaotic information environment\'97Signal war-planning leaks, state-secrets claims, and aggressive historical and cultural rewrites at the Smithsonian and universities\'97used less to govern competently than to disable accountability and entrench power.\
\
Week 10 Events\
\
Power and Authority\
\
1. President Donald Trump issued and then withdrew an executive order punishing law firm Paul Weiss by stripping clearances and contracts after extracting concessions (2025-03-22): The president used national security powers to threaten a major law firm\'92s livelihood and then traded relief for pro-bono work and internal policy changes, signaling that legal adversaries can be coerced through executive fiat.\
\
2. President Donald Trump ordered Attorney General Pam Bondi to refer partisan lawsuits to the White House and recommend punitive actions against involved law firms (2025-03-22): Directing the attorney general to channel disfavored litigation to the White House for punishment centralizes control over legal opposition and blurs the line between independent law enforcement and presidential retribution.\
\
3. President Donald Trump signed executive orders abolishing federal diversity, equity, and inclusion programs (2025-03-22): Eliminating DEI programs across the federal government reshapes hiring and workplace norms by executive decree, weakening institutional commitments to equal opportunity and representation without legislative debate.\
\
4. Trump administration cut federal funding for legal representation programs for unaccompanied migrant children (2025-03-22): Terminating contracts that fund lawyers for unaccompanied children in immigration court leaves vulnerable minors to face complex proceedings alone, undermining meaningful access to justice and due process.\
\
5. Acting Social Security Administration Commissioner Leland Dudek threatened to shut down SSA operations in response to a court order limiting data sharing with DOGE (2025-03-22): Threatening to halt Social Security services over a judicial privacy order leverages essential benefits as a bargaining chip in an inter-branch dispute, pressuring courts and risking harm to beneficiaries.\
\
6. U.S. Department of Education Office for Civil Rights found Maine\'92s education department in violation of Title IX over transgender sports participation and gave ten days to comply (2025-03-22): Reinterpreting Title IX to punish a state for allowing trans students to compete according to gender identity uses federal civil-rights enforcement to narrow protections and pressure state policy choices.\
\
7. President Donald Trump publicly denied signing a proclamation under the Alien Enemies Act authorizing rendition of Venezuelan migrants after aides said he had (2025-03-22): Conflicting statements about who authorized a sweeping deportation proclamation obscure accountability for a major rights-impacting decision and deepen confusion over the chain of command on immigration policy.\
\
8. President Donald Trump demanded a public apology from Maine Governor Janet Mills for refusing to enforce his transgender athlete ban (2025-03-22): Insisting that a governor apologize and submit to presidential authority over contested civil-rights policy illustrates pressure on state leaders to treat executive orders as unquestionable, narrowing space for lawful dissent.\
\
9. President Donald Trump issued an executive order imposing tariffs on imports from countries that buy Venezuelan oil (2025-03-24): Using emergency powers to penalize third countries over their energy trade with Venezuela extends unilateral economic coercion into trade policy, with limited oversight and potential collateral effects on global markets.\
\
